('SILA', '6707 NC 53 Hwy. East', '', 'Kelly', '28448', 'Bladen', '34.5831', '-78.4496', 'singletary.lake@ncparks.gov', '(910) 669-2928', '', '', '', '', 'Park Hoursrn8 a.m. - 5 p.m.rnClosed Christmas Day', 'Singletary Lake State Park is located in Bladen County on NC 53, 10 miles southeast of Elizabethtown and six miles east of White Lake.rnrnTo reach the park from Wilmington, drive north on US 421. Turn left onto NC 53 and travel west toward Elizabethtown. The park entrance, indicated by a large sign, will be on the right.rnrnTo arrive at Singletary Lake from Fayetteville, drive east on NC 53 for approximately 40 miles, drive through the town of Elizabethtown and continue east. The park entrance, marked with a large sign, is on the left.', '', '', '', '', '', 'Bring your group to Singletary Lake State Park and enjoy group camping in a land of mysterious origins. A portion of the unique Carolina bay ecosystem found nowhere else in the world, Singletary Lake lies within the 35,975-acre Bladen Lakes State Forest.rnrnDeveloped primarily for organized group camping, small craft boating, and pier fishing.  The park encompasses 649 acres of land and a 572-acre natural lake. In addition to listed activities, Singletary Lake State Park offers short hiking opportunities on site and nearly four miles of additional hiking trail, and fishing, at Bay Tree State Natural Area also.', '<img style=\\\"none\\\" src=\\\"pics/silafish.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"Fishing at Singletary Lake\\\" width=\\\"275px\\\"><p class=\\\"rightcol\\\"><span style=\\\"color:black; font-weight:bold;\\\">Get involved with North Carolina State Parks</span><br>Join a Friends group to promote, support, and advocate for our state parks system. Contact <a target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"http://www.ncfsp.org/\\\">Friends of State Parks</a>.', '', '', '', 0, 'Wilkerson9240,Wilkerson9240,Sponaugle7857,Bernhardt3627,Laubisch9544,Laubisch9544,Laubisch9544,Laubisch9544,Laubisch9544,Bernhardt3627,Bernhardt3627,Laubisch9544,Laubisch9544,Laubisch9544,Laubisch9544,Howard6319,Johnson0989,Allen0989,Allen0989,Higgin', 'In 1911 the North Carolina General Assembly declared that all state lakes of more than 500 acres in size, to include Singletary Lake, would be preserved as state properties for the use and enjoyment of all citizens.  ', 'Bring your group to Singletary Lake State Park and enjoy group camping in a land of mysterious origins. A portion of the unique Carolina bay ecosystem found nowhere else in the world, Singletary Lake lies within the 35,975-acre Bladen Lakes State Forest.rnrnDeveloped primarily for organized group camping, the park is comprised of 649 acres of land and a 572-acre natural lake. In addition to group camping, Singletary Lake State Park offers ample opportunities for nature study and recreation.', 'Origin of Carolina BaysrnPhotographs, models, games and investigations will be used to test some of the many theories explaining the formation of Carolina bays. Emphasis is placed on the physical characteristics of the Carolina bays, particularly their geomorphology.rnrnCarolina Bay EcologyrnThis interpretive theme focuses on the natural communities associated with the aquatic environment of bay lakes, the peat soils within the bays, and the mineral soils of the sand rims.  Key animal species, such as the red-cockaded woodpecker and the fox squirrel, are included.  Fire plays an important role in the ecology of the Carolina bays by creating and maintaining habitat for the plants and animals.', '', '2018-06-19 14:57:53', 30),
('SODI', '12700 Bayleaf Church Road', '', 'Raleigh', '27614', 'Wake', '', '', 'south.district@ncmail.org', '919-841-4059', '', '', '', '919-870-6843', '7:30 a.m. to 5:00 p.m.', '', '', 'Due to the strong storms yesterday, Jordan Lake power is out all over.  The main phone line is up due to the back-up generator but no internet use.  Ebenezer and New Hope boat ramps only are open and Vista Point group camps are up and running.  If you need to contact anyone there please call the main line at 919-362-0586.  Thanks  ', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 'Mitchener8455,Mitchener8455,Howard6319,Williams5894,', 'The purpose statement for this park has not yet been entered.', '', 'The interpretive themes for this park have not yet been entered.', '', '2016-12-15 18:25:40', 42),
('SOMO', '3001 South Mountain Park Avenue', '', 'Connelly Springs', '28612', 'Burke', '35.5963', '-81.6000', 'south.mountains@ncparks.gov', '(828) 433-4772', '(828) 433-4686', '', '', '(828) 433-4778', 'Park Hours\r\nOpen Daily (except Christmas Day) 7 a.m.\r\nClosing Hours\r\nDecember, January and February  7 p.m.\r\nNovember  8 p.m.\r\nMarch, April and October  9 p.m.\r\nMay - September  10 p.m.\r\nClosed Christmas Day\r\n\r\nPark Office Hours\r\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. weekdays and weekends\r\nClosed Christmas Day\r\n', 'South Mountains State Park is located in Burke County, 20.5 miles south of Morganton. From I-40, turn south on NC 18, travel 11.1 miles and make a right turn onto SR 1913 (Sugarloaf Road). Take SR 1913 to Old NC 18 4.3 miles and turn left. Travel 2.7 miles and make a right turn onto SR 1901 (Ward\'s Gap Road). The park is 1.4 miles off SR 1901 on SR 1904 (South Mountains Park Avenue).\r\n\r\nTravel one mile from the beginning of South Mountain Park Avenue to the South Mountains State Park gate. ', '13th Annual Nature Day Event Saturday, September 26th from 11am-3pm', 'A variety of programs, exhibits, hikes and music are scheduled for your enjoyment.  Food and beverages will be available for purchase. Contact the park office for more information at (828)433-4772', '', '', '2015-02-24 15:44:22', 'Nestled deep in the woods, South Mountains State Park is the perfect place to enjoy nature. Here you can see a majestic mountain range peeking out from the gently rolling landscape of the piedmont.\r\n\r\nThe park includes elevations up to 3,000 feet, a waterfall dropping 80 feet and more than 40 miles of trails. From equestrian camping to trout fishing, mountain biking to picnicking, a number of activities are available at South Mountains State Park.\r\n\r\nVisit one of the state\'s most rugged parks. Hike the trail to High Shoals Falls to witness the roar of the waterfall as it pours into a large pool. Backpack through the woodlands for primitive camping. Fish for trout in miles of mountain streams, or bicycle along the 17-mile mountain-bike loop.', '<img style=\"none\" src=\"pics/somoeques.jpg\" alt=\"horse riding at South Mountains State Park\" width=\"275px\"><p class=\"rightcol\"><span style=\"color:black; font-weight:bold;\">Get involved with North Carolina State Parks</span><br>Join a Friends group to promote, support, and advocate for our state parks system. Contact <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.ncfsp.org/\">Friends of State Parks</a>.', '', '', '', 0, 'Wagner0980,Wagner0980,Wagner0980,Laubisch9544,Lasley9759,Griffith0961,Griffith0961,Griffith0961,sigmon,sigmon,Wagner0980,sigmon,sigmon,Laubisch9544,Laubisch9544,Laubisch9544,Laubisch9544,Wagner0980,Wagner0980,Wagner0980,Huss6193,Griffith0961,Wagner09', 'The purpose statement for this park has not yet been entered.', 'Nestled deep in the woods, South Mountains State Park is the perfect place to enjoy nature. Here you can see a majestic mountain range peeking out from the gently rolling landscape of the Piedmont.  The park includes elevations up to 3,000 feet, a waterfall dropping 80 feet and more than 40 miles of trails. From equestrian camping to trout fishing, mountain biking to picnicking, a number of activities are available at South Mountains State Park.\r\n\r\nVisit one of the state\'s most rugged parks. Hike the trail to High Shoals Falls to witness the roar of the waterfall as it pours into a large pool. Backpack through the woodlands for primitive camping. Fish for trout in miles of mountain streams, or bicycle along the 17-mile mountain-bike loop.', 'Jacob\'s Fork Watershed Ecology\r\nThe study of the Jacob\'s Fork watershed ecology should focus on two areas:  The transition from Piedmont to Mountain in terrain and biotas, and the high quality of the watershed including the sensitive plants and animals that live in and around the river.', '', '2015-08-20 19:57:55', 31),
('STMO', '3042 Frank Parkway', '', 'Roaring Gap', '28668', 'Wilkes, Alleghany', '36.3873', '-81.0273', 'stone.mountain@ncparks.gov', '(336) 957-8185', '', '', '', '(336) 957-3985', 'Park HoursrnNovember - February, 7 a.m. - 7 p.m.rnMarch, April, October, 7 a.m. - 9 p.m.rnMay - September, 7 a.m. - 10 p.m.rnrnPlease note: Lower Gate on Longbottom Rd and all day use areas close one hour earlier. rnrnClosed Christmas DayrnrnPark Office Hoursrn8 a.m. - 5 p.m. daily, except closed weekends in January.rnClosed state holidays.rnrnFishing HoursrnYear-round, from 7:00 a.m. until one hour before park closes.rnrnPicnic Shelter HoursrnShelters close one hour before park closes.rnrnExhibit and Historic Site HoursrnExhibits: open during park office hours.rnHomestead site: open weekends, May through October. Visitors are welcome to walk the homestead site grounds when the site is not open.rnGarden Creek Baptist Church historic site: services are held at 9am every Sunday, May - October and first Sundays, November - April. Visitors are welcome to walk the church grounds when the church is closed.rnrnrn', 'Stone Mountain State Park is located in Wilkes and Alleghany counties, six miles southwest of Roaring Gap. From I-77 North, take Exit #83/Hwy 21 North/Sparta/Roaring Gap (you will exit from the left lane). Go north about 13 miles to Traphill Road/state road 1002, (you will see a brown state park sign) and turn left. Go about 4 miles to John P Frank Parkway (you will see a brown state park sign) and turn right. Follow the parkway to the park, about two miles.rnrnFrom the west, take NC 16 to NC 18 in North Wilkesboro and then turn right onto Hwy 268 East. Go about 3 miles and turn left at Airport Road. Go about 3 1/2 miles and turn left this becomes Traphill Rd (SR 1002). Follow Traphill Rd to  John P. Frank Parkway about 11 miles and turn left, follow the parkway to the park.', 'The Bridle Trail is CLOSED due to wet conditions.', '', 'The Bridle Trail(Horseback Riding)is CLOSED.rnrnArea Campgrounds...rnrnOld Fashion Day September 26, 2015 rnrn', 'The Bridle Trail(Horseback Riding)is Closed.rnrnArea Campgrounds - When our campground is full you may try these area campgrounds... Doughton Parkâ€“ Blue Ridge Pkwy MP 241, 336-372-8877; A & C Campgroundâ€“ two miles south of Sparta, 336-372-7905; New River State Park- Laurel Springs, 336-982-2587; Millerâ€™s Campingâ€“ Blue Ridge Pkwy MP 247, 336-359-2828; Cedar Rock Campground-Traphill, 336-957-8643.rnrnOld Fashion Day Saturday, September 26, 2015 from 11am to 4pm. Come out and join us for old fashion fun, games, & music. We will celebrate old time days of yesteryear.rn', '2016-10-08 08:10:46', 'Stone Mountain is not immediately visible upon entering the park that bears its name, but this magnificent 600-foot granite dome is well worth the wait. Sunlight and shadows dance across a broad tapestry of stone. White-tailed deer emerge from the security of the forest to graze on meadow grasses at the mountain\\\'s base. The scenery is only one attraction of the park.rnrnTest your fly-fishing techniques in more than 20 miles of designated trout waters. Or, with more than 18 miles of trails, take a hike in the park. Designated as a National Natural Landmark in 1975, Stone Mountain is bounded on the north by the Blue Ridge Parkway and on the west by the Thurmond Chatham Game Lands. More than 14,200 acres of mountain beauty offer opportunities for outdoor activities of all kinds.', '<img style=\\\"none\\\" src=\\\"pics/stmofishing.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"fishing at Stone Mountain State Park\\\" width=\\\"275px\\\"><p class=\\\"rightcol\\\"><span style=\\\"color:black; font-weight:bold;\\\">Get involved with North Carolina State Parks</span><br>Help start a Stone Mountain State Park Friends group to promote, support, and advocate for this special place in our state parks system. Contact <a target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"http://www.ncfsp.org/\\\">Friends of State Parks</a>.</p>', '', '', '', 0, 'Edwards3488,Edwards3488,Edwards3488,Edwards3488,Edwards3488,Edwards3488,Edwards3488,Brewer2398,Brewer2398,Brewer2398,Brewer2398,Brewer2398,Marquez2165,Marquez2165,Marquez2165,Marquez2165,Marquez2165,Marquez2165,Wood8771,Wood8771,Marquez2165,Marquez21', 'The purpose statement for this park has not yet been entered.', 'Stone Mountain is not immediately visible upon entering the park that bears its name, but this magnificent 600-foot granite dome is well worth the wait. Sunlight and shadows dance across a broad tapestry of stone. White-tailed deer emerge from the security of the forest to graze on meadow grasses at the mountain\\\'s base. The scenery is only one attraction of the park.rnrnTest your fly-fishing techniques in more than 20 miles of designated trout waters. Or, with more than 16 miles of trails, take a hike in the park. Designated as a National Natural Landmark in 1975, Stone Mountain is bounded on the north by the Blue Ridge Parkway and on the west by the Thurmond Chatham Game Lands. More than 14,100 acres of mountain beauty offer opportunities for outdoor activities of all kinds.', 'Geology of Stone MountainrnThe geologic formation known as Stone Mountain is a plutonic monadnock of granodiorite, an intrusive igneous rock similar to granite.  This rock formed from magma that intruded into surrounding older rock (biotite gneiss) during the Paleozoic era about 390 million years ago.  The overlying rock was removed through millions of years of erosion to expose the granodiorite dome known as Stone Mountain.', '', '2016-10-08 12:33:00', 32),
